  'd4562fc8-26ec-4a7c-8196-0f20892f7802',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Qwik Feature Folders — Structure That Works With the Optimizer$escape$,
  $escape$Qwik's optimizer splits code at `$` boundaries — your folder structure directly determines bundle granularity. Group by feature under `src/components/`, colocating the `component$`, its CSS module, and tests in one directory. Route-level features belong in `src/routes/` alongside their `layout.tsx`, `index.tsx`, and `plugin@` middleware files.

The tricky part is barrel exports. Qwik's optimizer traces import graphs to build lazy chunks. Wide barrels that re-export across multiple `$` boundaries force the optimizer to merge chunks that should stay separate, bloating your initial load. Keep each `index.ts` barrel shallow — only re-export the public `component$` and its prop types.

Never barrel-export `useTask$`, `useResource$`, or `server$` functions alongside UI components. These live in distinct lazy boundaries; merging them in one barrel causes the optimizer to pull server-only or deferred code into the same chunk as eagerly-loaded UI. One safe rule: if the symbol ends with `$`, don't let it escape through a shared barrel unless it's the component itself.$escape$,
  $escape$// src/components/auth/login/index.tsx
import { component$, useSignal } from '@builder.io/qwik';

export const Login = component$(() => {
  const email = useSignal('');
  return <input bind:value={email} type="email" placeholder="Email" />;
});

// src/components/auth/index.ts — shallow, safe barrel
export { Login } from './login';
// ❌ Never: export * from './login/login.server';
//    server$ lives in a separate lazy boundary — merging
//    it here forces the optimizer to bundle both chunks.$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
