INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '7bd71a88-46a4-4d60-b489-3cbccb6fc961',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Qwik Memoization — useComputed$ Helps, useCallback Doesn't Exist (By Design)$escape$,
  $escape$Qwik's resumable architecture makes React-style memoization mostly irrelevant. There's no useMemo, no useCallback, and no memo() HOC — because Qwik components don't re-execute as functions on state change. Only the fine-grained reactive scopes that depend on a changed signal re-run, surgically.

The one memoization primitive you'll reach for is useComputed$(). It creates a derived readonly signal that auto-tracks its signal dependencies — no dependency array required. It recomputes lazily, only when a tracked signal changes and its value is actually read.

Where it helps: expensive multi-signal derivations like filtered lists, aggregated stats, or formatted currency. Where it hurts: trivial expressions. Wrapping `signal.value + 's'` in useComputed$() adds a subscription graph node for zero benefit — just interpolate it inline in JSX.

Event handlers are $() QRLs — serialized, lazy-loaded, and stable by nature. The concept useCallback solves in React doesn't exist as a problem in Qwik.

Rule of thumb: reach for useComputed$() when the derivation is expensive or consumed by multiple JSX expressions. Otherwise, read signals directly.$escape$,
  $escape$import { component$, useSignal, useComputed$ } from '@builder.io/qwik';

export const Cart = component$(() => {
  const price = useSignal(49.99);
  const quantity = useSignal(2);
  const coupon = useSignal(0.1);

  // ✅ Auto-tracks all three signals, recomputes only when they change
  const total = useComputed$(
    () => price.value * quantity.value * (1 - coupon.value)
  );

  // ❌ Overkill — just use price.value directly in JSX
  // const label = useComputed$(() => `$${price.value}`);

  return <p>Total: ${total.value.toFixed(2)}</p>;
});$escape$,
