INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'e7b4a3a0-bd5c-4ce3-b7be-69b31aaaa130',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Qwik Forms — Controlled vs Uncontrolled, and the routeAction$ + zod$ Pattern$escape$,
  $escape$Qwik inverts the React Hook Form mental model entirely. Instead of client-managed state wired to validation libraries, reach for `routeAction$` + `zod$` — Qwik City's server-action primitive that validates before hydration even begins.

Controlled inputs — driven by `useSignal<string>('')` — make sense for real-time UI feedback like character counters or dependent selects. For everything else, uncontrolled native submission via `<Form action={action}>` is idiomatic Qwik: zero JS downloaded for the form, no event listeners registered until interaction.

`routeAction$` takes a `zod$` validator as its second argument. The schema runs server-side; `action.value.fieldErrors` surfaces per-field errors back to the component without shipping any validation code to the client bundle. Progressive enhancement is implicit — the form works before the JS chunk loads.

For complex client-side flows requiring `onChange` validation, use `modular-forms` — the Qwik-native RHF equivalent. It integrates directly with `useSignal` and respects Qwik's resumability: only the dirty field's signal invalidates, leaving the rest of the form tree untouched.$escape$,
  $escape$import { component$ } from '@builder.io/qwik';
import { routeAction$, zod$, z, Form } from '@builder.io/qwik-city';

export const useSignupAction = routeAction$(
  async (data) => {
    // data is fully typed and server-validated
    await db.users.create({ email: data.email });
    return { success: true };
  },
  zod$({ email: z.string().email(), password: z.string().min(8) })
);

export default component$(() => {
  const action = useSignupAction();
  return (
    <Form action={action}>
      <input name="email" />
      {action.value?.fieldErrors?.email && (
        <span>{action.value.fieldErrors.email}</span>
      )}
      <button type="submit">Sign up</button>
    </Form>
  );
});$escape$,
