INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '0b3f1fea-3dfe-4323-950d-78878f4494da',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Qwik i18n — qwik-speak, Intl API, and Why You Can't Just Drop in react-i18next$escape$,
  $escape$Qwik's resumability changes how i18n works. Unlike React where react-i18next hooks re-execute on hydration, Qwik serializes component state into HTML — translations must be available at SSR time and survive resumption without re-fetching. Use `qwik-speak` (the official Qwik i18n library), which integrates with Qwik's serialization pipeline via `QwikSpeakProvider` at the root.

Never hardcode strings. `useTranslate()` returns a `t()` function that resolves keys from locale JSON files, with inline fallbacks via the `@@` syntax: `t('nav.home@@Home')`. Interpolation is first-class: `t('price@@Price: {{val}}', { val })`.

For dates and numbers, use the `Intl` API directly. `useLocale()` from qwik-speak exposes the active locale object — pass its `lang` property (e.g., `'en-US'`) straight into `Intl.NumberFormat` or `Intl.DateTimeFormat`. This keeps formatting logic off the server bundle and executes lazily in the browser.

Locale switching updates a signal, so only components that read from it re-render — Qwik's fine-grained reactivity means zero full-tree re-renders on language change. Pair this with per-route lazy-loaded translation chunks to avoid shipping all locales upfront.$escape$,
  $escape$import { component$ } from '@builder.io/qwik';
import { useTranslate, useLocale } from 'qwik-speak';

export default component$(() => {
  const t = useTranslate();
  const { lang } = useLocale().value;

  const price = new Intl.NumberFormat(lang, {
    style: 'currency', currency: 'USD',
  }).format(1299.99);

  const date = new Intl.DateTimeFormat(lang, {
    dateStyle: 'medium',
  }).format(new Date());

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{t('home.title@@Welcome to ByteAI')}</h1>
      <p>{t('product.price@@Price: {{price}}', { price })}</p>
      <p>{date}</p>
    </div>
  );
});$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
