INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '918500bf-61a0-4055-a7d4-0eb2551de380',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Qwik Environment Config — Validate Env Vars at Startup with Zod$escape$,
  $escape$Qwik distinguishes sharply between server and browser environments — and your config strategy must too. Server-side secrets (API keys, DB URLs) live in `process.env` and are only accessible in `routeLoader$`, `server$`, or middleware. Browser-safe values must be prefixed with `PUBLIC_` to be exposed via `import.meta.env`. Hardcoding either is a liability.

Validate your entire env contract at server startup using Zod. Create a `src/env.server.ts` module that parses `process.env` with a Zod schema and throws immediately if any required var is missing or malformed. Import this module in your `plugin.ts` (Qwik City's server entry hook) so validation runs before any route handler executes. For public vars, create a parallel `src/env.public.ts` that reads from `import.meta.env` — safe to import in components. Never import `env.server.ts` from component files; Qwik's optimizer won't always catch that boundary violation for you, but your users will.$escape$,
  $escape$// src/env.server.ts
import { z } from 'zod';

const schema = z.object({
  DATABASE_URL: z.string().url(),
  GROQ_API_KEY: z.string().min(1),
  PUBLIC_APP_URL: z.string().url(),
});

export const env = schema.parse(process.env);

// src/routes/plugin.ts
import type { RequestHandler } from '@builder.io/qwik-city';
import '../env.server'; // throws at startup if vars missing

export const onRequest: RequestHandler = async ({ next }) => {
  await next();
};$escape$,
