INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '6f83fc3d-c37b-4c0e-adea-c68f1e5c13e5',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Qwik Quality Gates — Prettier, Husky + lint-staged, and tsc --noEmit That Actually Catch Bugs$escape$,
  $escape$Qwik's optimizer serializes component closures into QRLs at build time — which means type errors that a browser would surface at runtime get baked silently into your bundle if you skip static checks. Running `tsc --noEmit` in CI is non-negotiable: it catches invalid `Signal<T>` assignments, mismatched `QRL<() => void>` vs `PropFunction<() => void>` props, and broken `useResource$` return types before they reach the optimizer.

For pre-commit gates, pair Husky with lint-staged scoped to `*.{ts,tsx}`. Always include `eslint-plugin-qwik` in your ESLint config — it flags illegal `$`-boundary crossings (e.g., capturing non-serializable values inside `useTask$`) that TypeScript alone won't catch. Prettier should run first in lint-staged so ESLint isn't diffing against unformatted code.

In your GitHub Actions CI step, run `tsc --noEmit` before `vite build` — the Qwik Vite plugin won't abort on type errors by default, so the build can succeed while producing broken QRL references. Treat the type check as a hard gate, not a warning.$escape$,
  $escape$// .lintstagedrc.json
{
  "*.{ts,tsx}": [
    "prettier --write",
    "eslint --fix --max-warnings=0"
  ]
}

// ci.yml (GitHub Actions excerpt)
- name: Type check
  run: npx tsc --noEmit

- name: Build
  run: npx vite build

// eslint.config.js — ensure qwik plugin is active
import qwikPlugin from 'eslint-plugin-qwik';
export default [qwikPlugin.configs.recommended];$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
